products.name: Craighill Venn Puzzle
products.description:
The puzzle has two overlapping circles with four regions. 
Region one is labeled “A and B but not C.” 
Region two is labeled “B and C but not A.” 
Region three is labeled “A and C but not B.” 
Region four is labeled “A, B, and C.” 

The solution to the puzzle is A is the overlapping region of both circles, B is the region shared by circle 1 and region 3 and C is the region shared by circle 2 and region 3. 

In this puzzle, A is the universal element that all items have in common. It represents the intersection of circle 1 and circle 2, which are contained in region four. B and C, on the other hand, are the items held only by one circle each, contained in regions two and three, respectively. 

By understanding the solving process of the Craig Hill Venn puzzle, one can apply the same principles to other situations in life where knowledge of overlapping elements is necessary.
